It should be observecl that in early Latin the vei-bal nouns in tor (sor) do not al- ways bear the sense of being a habitual or perpetual agent, but are often used of a per- son who has only once exe- cuted the idea of the verb. Here e.g. castigator is not he who always or habitually blames Callicles, but who has done so only once--qui nuper me casti- gavit.

615. For subolet mihi ‘ I have an inkling of it', (ef. be- low 698,) see n. on Aul. 214. But sentire also means ‘I smell',

comp. the French cela sent mal.

617. quom, though causal, takes the indicative according to the habit of archaic Latin.
